<br>
Looking out over the breathtaking sunrise, she cleared her mind and sent a call to her lover. She sensed him stirring in his sleep, in his tent ... she thought to herself: “Ahh in the Dreadlands, he is close.” Before summoning him, rousing him from his peaceful slumber, she gracefully sat down, in her meditative stance. <br>
<br>
Turning inward, Malaehi reflected on the life she has known and began to cry, overcome by a complete sense of powerlessness. Never knowing her birth parents, ripped away from them and taken to serve the vile Vri’dril with the other kidnapped children, Malaehi was grateful that she barely had any memories of this time. Even after she and her new “sisters” were rescued, life was still difficult. Growing up in Nektulos, she was ever in fear of being caught, knowing the Teir’dal woman, she and her sisters loved as a Mother, was hated and banished by her own people. <br>
<br>
Malaehi’s face softened as she recollected the times she spent with her new family. Aye in that dark, terrifying forest, Malaehi knew happiness and showered unconditional affection and love on her sisters. Kaete was the Snowborn lass who mothered them all, while the twin Teir’dals, Malaeli and Malaeki, were always in whispers to each other sharing the bond that twins seem to have. The wraithlike human child Malae spent more time climbing trees and getting scrapes, caring not for the lessons of casting Mother Malaeliu taught. Malaele, the beautiful daughter of Erud was the most avid pupil of these lessons, hungering for the power of incantations. <br>
<br>
But, by far, Malaehi had the most love for the two babies, Malaekru - the Ogre , and Malaela, the Troll. Soft tears brimmed in her eyes, remembering how these two struggled so hard with their lessons, how they would both doze off, crushing Malaehi with their weight, deafening her with their chorus of snores. Mother Malaeliu would get so frustrated and send them off to hunt, the Ogress “barshing” and the Troll trotting along behind, casting heals. Every night, before going to bed they would cry and whine until Malaehi told them a story ... a story of love and far away places and beautiful dragons, promising that one day they would all hunt together and see these noble beasts of fame.<br>
<br>
Malaehi’s body shook with the pain she felt, letting the tears far freely. As the Gods would have it, that promise would never be kept. Just when life in the forest had a semblance of order and routine, the time came for the girls to pass their Age of Release. The Gods would claim each one for their servitude, transporting the girls back to their original lands of birth - blurring all memory of the past until they were old enough to handle the truth. <br>
<br>
Malaehi stood up and glared at the sky “Why do WE not have a choice?! I had a family, and it was taken away. I found a new family and again it was taken away. Are we mere toys for your amusement?!!” Her voice echoed off the mountain, reaching back to her renewing the anguish.<br>
<br>
She slumped against the cool stone leg of one of the guardian statues, and wrapped her arms around it, hugging it ... longing to be hugged back. “...and now? What choice do I have... to love and lose my new family, the Lions ... or to lose the love I have...?” <br>
<br>
Numbness swept over Malaehi, as she stood there hugging the lifeless statue for hours. Pulling away finally, Malaehi cleared her mind of all thoughts, all feelings. she had decided to make a choice and to let it be her decision... to take fate into her own hands...<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ <br>
&quot;Omnia vincit amor&quot; ~~ &quot;Love conquers all&quot; ~ Erollisi Marr, Goddess of Love<br>
